projects:
[{'title': 'Large Scale Insect Rearing in Relation to Animal Welfare', 'date': {'start': {'month': 9, 'day': None, 'year': 2012}, 'end': {'month': 10, 'day': None, 'year': 2012}}, 'description': "This project was commissioned by VENIK (stands for VEreniging Nederlandse Insecten Kwekers, i.e. Dutch Association of Insect Breeders) and it was carried out in the context of ACT (Academic Consultancy Training), a compulsory course in Wageningen Master's Programs, which is regarded as professional experience in consultancy. 
the insect rearing sector is a dynamic, fast growing sector in the Netherlands. Insects are produced mainly as feed for pets and animals in zoos, but many other uses are possible. The scope of the project was to explore how the expected up-scaling of insect breeding can be achieved in an insect-friendly manner taking into account the current legislation framework both in the European Union and in the Netherlands.
The final report was used as the basis for a presentation and publication in the EurSafe Conference, which was held in Uppsala, Sweden in September 2013.
